<caption>

A double <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../547/511547.xml">
quantum dot</link>.  The electron spins SL and SR would each define one quantum two-level system, or <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../284/25284.xml">
qubit</link></it> in the Loss-DiVincenzo proposal
</caption>
</image>

The <b>Loss-DiVincenzo quantum computer</b> (or spin-qubit quantum computer) is a scalable <link>
semiconductor-based quantum computer</link>  that was proposed by <scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../443/8486443.xml">
Daniel Loss</link></scientist>
 and <link>
David P. DiVincenzo</link> in 1997<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref>.  This proposal would use the intrinsic spin-1/2 degree of freedom of individual electrons confined to <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../547/511547.xml">
quantum dots</link> as <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../284/25284.xml">
qubits</link>.  
